Fig. 7 a shows the relation between the adsorption capacity (
q e
) and the time of contact/interaction between the catalyst and the molecules of dyes. As seen, through the first 30 min of contact/interaction, the adsorption of MB molecules on PVA/ZnO2 and PVA/CZnO2 reached 95% of equilibrium (
q e
). This is attributed to the rapid adsorption of the dye molecules on the catalysts that takes place instantaneously thanks to the surface interactions and fast diffusion of the dye molecules through the matrix. It is clear that between 30 and 60 min, partial saturation was achieved for the adsorption sites, with a slow rate, and after 60 min full equilibrium was achieved. In general, the mechanism of the dye adsorption on the solid absorbents follows distinct stages [2,37,38]. 1st stage is correlated to the movement of dye molecules to the outer surface of the catalyst when they are displaced from the surrounding solution. 2nd stage is correlated to MB molecules diffusion through the interfaces between the solid and solution (solid/solution) and 3rd stage is related to interaction between the molecules of methylene blue and the sites of adsorption located on the inner surface of catalyst. Finally, the molecules of dye are diffused and inter-penetrated into the pores of solid catalyst. When the pores are inter-connected, this diffusion through the surface improved, such as this present case.

Fig. 8 a shows the impact of the initial concentration of the dye (Co) on the capacity of adsorption (
q e
) for both PVA/ZnO2 and PVA/CZnO2 catalysts. As seen, the values of (
q e
) are significantly influenced by the initial concentration of the dye (Co), where the values of (
q e
) increased by increasing the concentration of dye from 1500 to 2000 mg/L. Interestingly, with increasing the concentration of dye higher than 2000 mg/L, the values of (
q e
) did not change (no significant effect was detected). This behavior is due to the increase in dye concentration >2000 mg/L that leads to an increase in the number of adsorption sites adsorbed on the catalyst and make the system reach saturation [2]. It is worth to mention that the difference between the values of
q e
for both catalysts (PVA/ZnO2 and PVA/CZnO2) increases at the dye concentration >2000 mg/L. This behavior is attributed to the early adsorption sites saturation on the catalysts. The isotherm models of Temkin and Dubinin-Radushkevich, Langmuir (types I and II) and Freundlich were used to analyze the equilibrium data. It is known that these models deal with the interactions between the catalyst and adsorbate/dye and the distribution of adsorbate from the solution to catalyst up to equilibrium [2]. In fact, the importance of the isotherm models renders to their ability to explain the mechanism of adsorbent-adsorbate interaction. This understanding allows adjusting the adsorption process.
